Title: An Interactive Computer Model for Defibrillation Device Design  
Author: John A. Schmidty Christopher R. Johnsony Robert S. MacLeodz 
Keyword: Defibrillation Interactive Computer Model Finite Element Method  
Address: Building  Building 500  Salt Lake City, Utah 84112, U.S.A.  
Affiliation: yDepartment of Computer Science, 3190 Merrill Engineering  zCardiovascular Research and Training Institute,  University of Utah  
Abstract: We have developed an interactive computer model for defibrillation device design utilzing the Utah Torso Model [1]. This system allows researchers to interactively design and place electrodes into a high-resolution finite element model of the human thorax to investigate fields generated from electrical shocks. Several quantitative measures are used to determine the efficacy of different electrode configurations thus providing a useful tool for evaluating a wide variety of electrode configurations in an efficient manner. Currently the most promising electrode configuration candidates are being tested in animals as well as in clinical enviroments. 
